<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>feed the fish • feed the fishes</xh5><p> <i>feed the fish</i>—(U.S. sl.) be sea-sick; vomit: I opened the hatch, stepped out and then I knew I was going to <u>feed the fish</u>.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>feed the goldfish</b>—(euph.) leave the company to go to the toilet: The variations on these expressions are endless and include: go and feed a dog, go and <u>feed the goldfish</u>...</p><p> <i>feed the fishes—</i>1. <i>(UK)</i> be drowned <i>(also: be food for fishes):</i> They found the boat but they didn’t find him. So he must be <u>feeding the fishes</u>. 2. <i>= feed the fish:</i> The sea never affects me, but my unfortunate brother spent most of his time <u>feeding the fishes</u>.</p> </entry>
